<HEADLINE>
<P>
BOYARSKY ON L.A. COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Having known Bill Boyarsky for a good many years, I was disappointed in his 
first effort as columnist in the Metro section ("Government by Five Soloists," 
Sept. 29). His column read as though he has been in hibernation for perhaps 8 
or 9 years. 
</P>
<P>
The balance of power on the Board of Supervisors has moved among the members 
according to each particular issue. For example, the debate over contracting 
out county services was settle in 1978 when nearly two-thirds of the voters of 
Los Angeles County voted in support of this kind of government economy and 
efficiency. Supervisors Deane Dana, Pete Schabarum and I supported the voters' 
decision. It was opposed by Supervisors Kenny Hahn and Ed Edelman. 
</P>
<P>
However, it was with the support of Dana and Edelman that I was able to push 
forward with the construction of the new Olive View Medical Center. Schabarum 
opposed this critically needed facility. 
</P>
<P>
Dana, Schabarum and I opposed the distribution of bleach kits and so-called 
clean needles in the fight against AIDS because we believe money is better 
spent on drug education for our young people and in helping get addicts off of 
drugs. 
</P>
<P>
Regarding my interests in promoting healthy diets, the board acted unanimously 
in 1981 with an order that improved the type of foods served in our probation 
facilities. 
</P>
<P>
The board has seen various alliances form and dissolve from time to time, and 
this accrues to the benefit of all our citizens. Admittedly, we are five very 
different individuals. At the same time, each of us was elected by a different 
constituency and each of us has particular obligations to our district. 
</P>
<P>
But the record would bear out the fact that we are extremely successful in 
attaining a high degree of teamwork. For your information (and Boyarsky's), the 
board is unanimous on approximately 95% of each weekly calendar. 
</P>
<P>
MICHAEL D. ANTONOVICH 
</P>
<P>
Supervisor, Fifth District 
</P>
</TEXT>
