<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUP ATTEMPT AGAINST GEN. NORIEGA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In response to "Bush Takes Residence in an Indecisive House of Halfway 
Measures," by Charles Krauthammer, Op-Ed Page, Oct. 6: 
</P>
<P>
This column claims that the United States government should have intervened in 
the failed Panamanian coup. It viciously slashed at President Bush's lack of 
action in what appeared to be an attempt to overthrow Noriega. 
</P>
<P>
I would just like to point out that the rebels were not freedom-loving 
democratic white knights. They were a bunch of power-hungry Noriega wanna-bes 
who wished to " . . . help him retire quietly." This was not a coup. Rather, it 
was a feeble attempt to wrest power away from Noriega by his own followers. 
This is clearly illustrated by the fact that they neglected to eliminate 
Noriega when they had the chance. These rebels did not want to change 
Panamanian society for the better; nor did they want to right the social 
injustices and cruel inhumanities wrought by Noriega's regime. They wanted 
power for themselves. They were motivated purely by greed. 
</P>
<P>
Now I ask Krauthammer: Why should the U.S. involve itself in the petty internal 
affairs of some Latin American nation, when the involvement could only hinder 
American foreign policy objectives in Central America? Is it worth it to get 
rid of one "two-bit drug-runner?" 
</P>
<P>
CHRIS LOHR 
</P>
<P>
San Clemente 
</P>
</TEXT>
