<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUP ATTEMPT AGAINST GEN. NORIEGA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Another day, another congressional outcry. On Oct. 4, the day after the failed 
military revolt against Noriega, senators and representative like Sen. David 
Boren (D-Okla.) and Rep. Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), respectfully blasted the Bush 
Administration for doing too little to help the insurgents (Part I). Boren, a 
usual opponent of covert action against Noriega, said Bush should have ordered 
U.S. military intervention while the rebels held the headquarters of the 
Panamanian Defense Forces. Likewise, Hyde thought the U.S. missed a perfect 
opportunity to resolve the Noriega problem. 
</P>
<P>
While these senators and representatives talk about blown chances, they fail to 
see the most powerful weapon in front of them. This weapon is patience. By 
being patient, the United States will eventually capture Noriega. Noriega can 
escape bullets, rockets, and coups but he cannot escape time. 
</P>
<P>
KEN HEMPY 
</P>
<P>
San Clemente 
</P>
