<HEADLINE>
<P>
REPARATIONS FOR JAPANESE INTERNEES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I want to applaud The Times for its advocacy on behalf of the 117,000 Japanese 
Americans who were forcibly interned by the American government during World 
War II (editorial, "For Redress at Last," Oct. 3). In August, 1988, when 
President Reagan signed the act into law to provide speedy monetary 
compensation and an apology to the Japanese American citizens unjustly 
imprisoned, the former internees finally felt that this stain of injustice 
would soon be purged away. 
</P>
<P>
But, one year later, no monies have been appropriated and more than 2,400 
internees have died, separated from final justice by a barbed-wire fence of 
promises made, promises broken, promises unfulfilled. 
</P>
<P>
I urge Congress, on behalf of the American people, to keep its word. Justice 
delayed is justice denied. As the leader of the free world, America can exhort 
other nations to guarantee human rights, but only when it fulfills its own 
moral and legal obligations at home. 
</P>
<P>
JONATHAN T. KAJI 
</P>
<P>
Gardena 
</P>
</TEXT>
