<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: JUDGE REFUSES TO BLOCK TRIAL OF JUANITA ST. 
JOHN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Los Angeles Superior Court judge on Friday denied the latest attempt by 
lawyers for Juanita St. John to head off a trial of the embattled head of a 
city-funded Africa trade task force. 
</P>
<P>
Judge Ronald Swearinger denied an appeal by St. John that sought to throw out 
an earlier court ruling that St. John stand trial on a misdemeanor charge of 
violating a city subpoena. The subpoena seeks records and information on how 
St. John spent $180,000 in city funds. A pretrial hearing has been set for Oct. 
24. 
</P>
<P>
In addition to the alleged subpoena violation, St. John, a business associate 
of Mayor Tom Bradley, and the Task Force for Africa/Los Angeles Relations, 
which is run by St. John, are under investigation by Los Angeles police and the 
district attorney's major fraud unit. Investigators are trying to determine if 
city funds were misused. 
</P>
<P>
St. John and her attorneys have said the funds were spent properly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
BRADLEY, TOM; ST JOHN, JUANITA; TASK FORCE FOR AFRICA LOS ANGELES RELATIONS; 
LOS ANGELES -- GOVERNMENT OFFICIALS; LOS ANGELES -- GOVERNMENT AGENCIES; 
CONFLICT OF INTEREST; GOVERNMENT MISCONDUCT; MISUSE OF PUBLIC FUNDS; ETHICS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA101489-0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 120573 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 14, 1989, Saturday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
